    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal can be quite frustrating, but it's all part of the loan's magic. Think of your student loan as a mountain of gold guarded by a dragon named Interest. Every month, you give the dragon a portion of your gold, but it doesn't just vanish. Instead, the dragon takes a little extra for its own hoard. This extra is the interest. Your principal, the mountain of gold, doesn't shrink immediately because the dragon takes its share first. Only after the dragon has taken its cut does the dragon give you back a portion of your gold, and that's what reduces your principal. So, while you're giving the dragon your gold, the mountain doesn't shrink much at first because the dragon is still growing its hoard. But over time, as you continue to give the dragon your gold, you'll start to see the mountain shrink. It's just that the dragon's hoard grows faster than the mountain shrinks, at least at the beginning. Patience, my friend, and keep giving the dragon your gold, and eventually, you'll see the mountain shrink.",
